-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.33ex; height:2.009ex;" alt=3D"{\textstyle {\bar {=
x}}}"></span>, marked with a diamond. The blue intervals contain <i>=CE=BC<=
/i>, and the red ones do not.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, a <b>confidence interval</b> (<b>CI</b>) is a range of=
 values used to estimate an unknown <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Statistical_parameter" title=3D"Statistical parameter">statistical parame=
ter</a>, such as a population <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean=
" title=3D"Mean">mean</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-using_confidently_1-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval=
#cite_note-using_confidently-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Rather than reporting a single p=
oint estimate (e.g. "the average screen time is 3 hours per day"), a confid=
ence interval provides a range, such as 2 to 4 hours, along with a specifie=
d <b>confidence level</b>, typically 95%.=20
</p><p>A 95% confidence level does not imply a 95% probability that the tru=
e parameter lies within a particular calculated interval. The confidence le=
vel instead reflects the long-run reliability of the method used to generat=
e the interval.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dekking_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Dekking-2">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In other wor=
ds, if the same sampling procedure were repeated 100 times from the same po=
pulation, approximately 95 of the resulting intervals would be expected to =
contain the true population mean.
</p>
