<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Interpretation">Interpretat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DConfiden=
ce_interval&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Inter=
pretation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>Various interpretations of a confidence interval can be given (taking th=
e 95% confidence interval as an example in the following).
</p>
<ul><li>The confidence interval can be expressed in terms of a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequentist_probability" title=3D"Frequentist =
probability">long-run frequency</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Replication_(statistics)" title=3D"Replication (statistics)">repeated =
samples</a> (or in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resampling_(sta=
tistics)" title=3D"Resampling (statistics)">resampling</a>): "Were this pro=
cedure to be repeated on numerous samples, the proportion of calculated 95%=
 confidence intervals that encompassed the true value of the population par=
ameter would tend toward 95%."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CH_6-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-C=
H-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup></li>
<li>The confidence interval can be expressed in terms of probability with r=
espect to a single theoretical (yet to be realized) sample: "There is a 95%=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coverage_probability" title=3D"Co=
verage probability">probability</a> that the 95% confidence interval calcul=
ated from a given future sample will cover the true value of the population=
 parameter."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Neyman_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Neyman-7"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> This essentially reframes the "repeated samples" interpretation as a =
probability rather than a frequency.</li>
<li>The confidence interval can be expressed in terms of statistical signif=
icance, e.g.: "The 95% confidence interval represents values that are not <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistically_significant" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistically significant">statistically significant=
ly</a> different from the point estimate at the .05 level."<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confide=
nce_interval#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-center" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:95%25_confidence_interval.svg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/f/f4/95%25_confidence_interval.svg/500px-95%25_confidence_interval.s=
vg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"369" height=3D"224" class=3D"mw-file-el=
ement" data-file-width=3D"1657" data-file-height=3D"1005"></a><figcaption>I=
nterpretation of the 95% confidence interval in terms of statistical signif=
icance</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Common_misunderstandings">C=
ommon misunderstandings</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DConfidence_interval&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D=
"Edit section: Common misunderstandings"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Neyman_Construction_Confidence_Intervals.png"=
 class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Neyman_Construction_Confidence_Intervals.png/250p=
x-Neyman_Construction_Confidence_Intervals.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"672" data=
-file-height=3D"671"></a><figcaption>A plot of 50 confidence intervals from=
 50 samples generated from a normal distribution</figcaption></figure>
<p>Confidence intervals and levels are frequently misunderstood, and publis=
hed studies have shown that even professional scientists often misinterpret=
 them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>A 95% confidence level does not mean that for a given realized inte=
rval there is a 95% probability that the population parameter lies within t=
he interval.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Morey_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Morey-10"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-:2-11"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>A 95% confidence level does not mean that 95% of the sample data lie wi=
thin the confidence interval.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-using_confidently_1-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interv=
al#cite_note-using_confidently-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>A 95% confidence level does not mean that there is a 95% probability of=
 the parameter estimate from a repeat of the experiment falling within the =
confidence interval computed from a given experiment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2=
_11-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confide=
nce_interval#cite_note-:2-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>For example, suppose a factory produces metal rods. A random sample of 2=
5 rods gives a 95% confidence interval for the population mean length of 36=
.8 to 39.0&nbsp;mm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tan_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Tan-12"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>It is incorrect to say that there is a 95% probability that the tru=
e population mean lies within this interval, because the true mean is fixed=
, not random. For example, it might be 37&nbsp;mm, which is within the conf=
idence interval, or 40&nbsp;mm, which is not; in any case, whether it falls=
 between 36.8 and 39.0&nbsp;mm is a matter of fact, not probability.</li>
<li>It is not necessarily true that the lengths of 95% of the sampled rods =
lie within this interval. In this case, it cannot be true: 95% of 25 is not=
 an integer.</li>
<li>It is incorrect to say that if we took a second sample, there is a 95% =
probability that the sample mean length (an estimate of the population mean=
 length) would fall within this interval. In fact, if the true mean length =
is far from this specific confidence interval, it could be very unlikely th=
at the next sample mean falls within the interval.</li></ul>
<p>Instead, the 95% confidence level means that if we took 100 such samples=
, we would expect the true population mean to lie within approximately 95 o=
f the calculated intervals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-using_confidently_1-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval=
#cite_note-using_confidently-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Morey_10-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_inte=
rval#cite_note-Morey-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_11-2" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite=
_note-:2-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tan_12-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Tan-1=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Comparison_with_prediction_=
intervals">Comparison with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Predict=
ion_interval" title=3D"Prediction interval">prediction intervals</a></h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DConfidence_interva=
l&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Comparison with=
 prediction intervals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A confidence interval is used to estimate a population parameter, such a=
s the mean. For example, the expected value of a fair six-sided die is 3.5.=
 Based on repeated sampling, after computing many 95% confidence intervals,=
 roughly 95% of them will contain 3.5 (and the width of the confidence inte=
rval shrinks with sample size).
</p><p>A prediction interval, on the other hand, provides a range within wh=
ich a future individual observation is expected to fall with a certain prob=
ability. In the case of a single roll of a fair six-sided die, an exact 95%=
 prediction interval does not exist. However, there are exact 95% predictio=
n intervals for rolling a twenty-sided die.  One such interval is <span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mat=
hml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"ht=
tp://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle [1,19]}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">[</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mn>19</mn>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">]</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle [1,19]}</anno=
tation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/557dc5636ac7bfaf4208f688510544a1d203d3f2" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:5.815ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle [1,=
19]}"></span>, since 95% of the time the roll will result in a 19 or less, =
and the remaining 5% will result in a 20.
</p><p>The key distinction is that confidence intervals quantify uncertaint=
y in estimating parameters, while prediction intervals quantify uncertainty=
 in forecasting future observations.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Comparison_with_credible_in=
tervals">Comparison with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credible_=
interval" title=3D"Credible interval">credible intervals</a></h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DConfidence_interval&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Comparison with credibl=
e intervals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>In many common settings, such as estimating the mean of a normal distrib=
ution with known variance,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-13"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> confidence intervals coincide with credible intervals under non-info=
rmative priors. In such cases, common misconceptions about confidence inter=
vals (e.g. interpreting them as probability statements about the parameter)=
 may yield practically correct conclusions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Examples_of_how_na=C3=AFve_=
interpretation_of_confidence_intervals_can_be_problematic"><span id=3D"Exam=
ples_of_how_na.C3.AFve_interpretation_of_confidence_intervals_can_be_proble=
matic"></span>Examples of how na=C3=AFve interpretation of confidence inter=
vals can be problematic</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DConfidence_interval&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D=
"Edit section: Examples of how na=C3=AFve interpretation of confidence inte=
rvals can be problematic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
