</p><p>This example is used to argue against na=C3=AFve interpretations of =
confidence intervals. If a confidence procedure is asserted to have propert=
ies beyond that of the nominal coverage (such as relation to precision, or =
a relationship with Bayesian inference), those properties must be proved; t=
hey do not follow from the fact that a procedure is a confidence procedure.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Confidence_procedure_for_=
=CF=892"><span id=3D"Confidence_procedure_for_.CF.892"></span>Confidence pr=
ocedure for <i>=CF=89</i><sup>2</sup></h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DConfidence_interval&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Confidence procedure for =CF=892"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Steiger<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> suggested=
 a number of confidence procedures for common <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Effect_size#Omega-squared_(%CF%892)" title=3D"Effect size">effe=
ct size</a> measures in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_o=
f_variance" title=3D"Analysis of variance">ANOVA</a>. Morey et al.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Morey_10-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Morey-10"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> point out th=
at several of these confidence procedures, including the one for <i>=CF=89<=
/i><sup>2</sup>, have the property that as the <i>F</i> statistic becomes i=
ncreasingly small=E2=80=94indicating misfit with all possible values of <i>=
=CF=89</i><sup>2</sup>=E2=80=94the confidence interval shrinks and can even=
 contain only the single value <i>=CF=89</i><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0; t=
hat is, the CI is infinitesimally narrow (this occurs when <span class=3D"m=
we-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inl=
ine mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://ww=
w.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle p\geq 1-\alpha /2}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=A5<!-- =E2=89=A5 --></mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mn>2</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle p\geq 1-\alph=
a /2}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7d22a68f40a1a98306147a45fb3216ee20048601" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; margin-left: -0.089ex; width:12.173ex; height:2.843ex;" a=
lt=3D"{\displaystyle p\geq 1-\alpha /2}"></span> for a <span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline =
mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 100(1-\alpha )\%}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>100</mn>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">%<!-- % --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 100(1-\alpha =
)\%}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7b89848010e0361a7b21502f3d458f66cd70dff5" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:12.723ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 10=
0(1-\alpha )\%}"></span> CI).
</p><p>This behavior is consistent with the relationship between the confid=
ence procedure and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hyp=
othesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hypothesis test=
ing">significance testing</a>: as <i>F</i> becomes so small that the group =
means are much closer together than we would expect by chance, a significan=
ce test might indicate rejection for most or all values of <i>=CF=89</i><su=
p>2</sup>. Hence the interval will be very narrow or even empty (or, by a c=
onvention suggested by Steiger, containing only 0). However, this does <i>n=
ot</i> indicate that the estimate of <i>=CF=89</i><sup>2</sup> is very prec=
ise. In a sense, it indicates the opposite: that the trustworthiness of the=
 results themselves may be in doubt. This is contrary to the common interpr=
etation of confidence intervals that they reveal the precision of the estim=
ate.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DConfidence_interval&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Methods for calculating confidence intervals for the binomial proportion=
 appeared from the 1920s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-18"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The main ideas=
 of confidence intervals in general were developed in the early 1930s,<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Neyman1934_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Neyman1934-20"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Neyman1970_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Neyman1970-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the first t=
horough and general account was given by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Jerzy_Neyman" title=3D"Jerzy Neyman">Jerzy Neyman</a> in 1937.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Neyman_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Neyman-7"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Neyman described the development of the ideas as follows (reference =
numbers have been changed):<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Neyman1970_22-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_=
note-Neyman1970-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>[My work on confidence intervals] originated about 1930 from a simple qu=
estion of Waclaw Pytkowski, then my student in Warsaw, engaged in an empiri=
cal study in farm economics. The question was: how to characterize non-dogm=
atically the precision of an estimated regression coefficient? ...
</p><p>Pytkowski's monograph ... appeared in print in 1932.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confid=
ence_interval#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It so happened that, somewhat earli=
er, Fisher published his first paper<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note=
-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> concerned with fiducial distributions and fiducial argumen=
t. Quite unexpectedly, while the conceptual framework of fiducial argument =
is entirely different from that of confidence intervals, the specific solut=
ions of several particular problems coincided. Thus, in the first paper in =
which I presented the theory of confidence intervals, published in 1934,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Neyman1934_20-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-Neyman1934-20"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> I recognized Fisher's priority for the idea that interval estimation is p=
ossible without any reference to Bayes' theorem and with the solution being=
 independent from probabilities <i>a priori</i>. At the same time I mildly =
suggested that Fisher's approach to the problem involved a minor misunderst=
anding.
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In medical journals, confidence intervals were promoted in the 1970s but=
 only became widely used in the 1980s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_no=
te-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> By 1988, medical journals were requiring the reporting o=
f confidence intervals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval#cite_note-26"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
